<span id="freeTextContainer13044425066371980202">A concise and straightforward introduction to the practice of meditation, awareness, compassion, integrity. It steers away from dogma on the parts that might trouble the sceptic such as Karma and reincarnation, recommending a resounding &quot;I don&apos;t know&quot; as the only possible reasonable attitude - which is fair enough I suppose, since no-one can know. I have to say that the first part, Basics, was fine with me, but I began to have the allergic reaction in the second and third sections, where it tend</span>
  <span id="freeText13044425066371980202" style="display:none">A concise and straightforward introduction to the practice of meditation, awareness, compassion, integrity. It steers away from dogma on the parts that might trouble the sceptic such as Karma and reincarnation, recommending a resounding "I don't know" as the only possible reasonable attitude - which is fair enough I suppose, since no-one can know. I have to say that the first part, Basics, was fine with me, but I began to have the allergic reaction in the second and third sections, where it tends to that kind of esoteric psycho-babble that just sets my teeth on edge. Buddhism as portrayed here may be a way of life rather than a set of beliefs, but it does, nevertheless, start from one basic premise that I can't subscribe to: this idea that life is <em>dukkha</em>, a Pali word encompassing suffering, pain, anguish, disquietude, stress, misery, frustration. Naaaah. Life is good.<br /><br />PS: English version is <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/90557.Buddhism_without_Beliefs" title="Buddhism without Beliefs by Stephen Batchelor" rel="nofollow noopener">Buddhism without Beliefs</a></span>
