        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2940665425" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7757469719830717940">I enjoyed this brief, wise book. I read it by the shores of Lake Winnipesuakee over the past week while on vacation, and I&apos;ve been pondering the author&apos;s lessons and observations. Batchelor is an agnostic: he claims, again and again, that the proper response to metaphysical questions about life after death, about reincarnation, about other unknowables is, &quot;I don&apos;t know.&quot; The author is secular Buddhist: he has no beliefs in karma or the supernatural, and he spends some time early in the book desc</span>
  <span id="freeText7757469719830717940" style="display:none">I enjoyed this brief, wise book. I read it by the shores of Lake Winnipesuakee over the past week while on vacation, and I've been pondering the author's lessons and observations. Batchelor is an agnostic: he claims, again and again, that the proper response to metaphysical questions about life after death, about reincarnation, about other unknowables is, "I don't know." The author is secular Buddhist: he has no beliefs in karma or the supernatural, and he spends some time early in the book describing how the Buddha's teachings become a religion instead of a practice for a great many people. For example, one startlingly original observation related to the Four Noble Truths, which--according to the author--are actions one should take, not dogma one should believe it. They are a 'do' and not a 'believe.' (I found that idea to jibe with my own observations about some of the messages of Jesus). <br /><br />The author writes that the key question any one of us should ask is this: if death is certain, and the time of death is uncertain, what should I do? While that seems morbid on the surface, it is actually incredibly liberating and clarifying. This is the mindset of the undeluded. The past is gone, the future is uncertain, and the only guarantee is right now, so...see it! Be it! Live it, right now, this very moment. <br /><br />As I read this particular passage, and was thinking about it, my eyes fell upon a large tree in the yard of the house where I was staying. This tree had been in my line of sight for several days; literally right in front of me...but I never saw it. When I focused on this tree, and truly looked at it...I was amazed. There right in front of me was this massive life form, decades old, living its life in peace and quiet. The bark has spots of lichen growing on it, and on two occasions, a bald eagle landed in its branches, right above my head! Remarkable...and invisible to me as I busily thought and thought and thought without seeing the world around me. Imagine if we could 'see' like that everywhere and always! The world is right in front of us, but--as the author says--we are our own jailers, and the prison is mindlessness and habit. <br /><br />So I am hoping to cultivate some more awakening in my own life, seeing more of what's in front of me, and not numbly travelling through life as often as I do, lost in my own head, not enjoying what I have come to call The Tao of -Is. This is an insightful book that I will turn to again and again. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7757469719830717940" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

