<div id="review_1930123555" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1930123555" />
    <a title="PhebeAnn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64411069-phebeann"><img alt="PhebeAnn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485740233p2/64411069.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1930123555?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="PhebeAnn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="PhebeAnn" href="/user/show/64411069-phebeann">PhebeAnn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64411069-phebeann?shelf=buddhism">buddhism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1930123555" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12603857108945840838">This is a contemplative book that unfolds lyrically and quizzically, almost in the tradition of a koan. I think that Batchelor&apos;s point could have been made even more briefly than he does in what is effectively a 115 page extended essay, but perhaps it would have then lost some of its contemplative quality and in some way maybe &quot;feeling&quot; less Buddhist. His point is an important contribution to contemporary Buddhism though as he points out he is not the only one to make it: you don&apos;t have to belie</span>
  <span id="freeText12603857108945840838" style="display:none">This is a contemplative book that unfolds lyrically and quizzically, almost in the tradition of a koan. I think that Batchelor's point could have been made even more briefly than he does in what is effectively a 115 page extended essay, but perhaps it would have then lost some of its contemplative quality and in some way maybe "feeling" less Buddhist. His point is an important contribution to contemporary Buddhism though as he points out he is not the only one to make it: you don't have to believe in God to be a Buddhist, and in fact, Buddhism is probably better aligned with agnosticism and a deep appreciation and understanding of mortality (rather than an eternal gaze towards rebirth/afterlife). I also appreciated his pairing, towards the end of the book, of American libertarian notions of freedom with Buddhist notions of freedom and his brief discussion of how these can work together to improve one another. In a way, this book is quite post-structuralist/post-modern because it really wants to emphasize the lack of concreteness in Buddhism: its more deconstructionist side where we come to know that we do not know.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12603857108945840838" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

